\title{Cognionics HD-72: Serial Acquisition Log}
\taxon{experiment}
\author{barton-rhodes}
\date{2026-04-05}
\import{macros}
\tag{eeg}
\tag{cognionics}
\tag{serial}
\tag{protocol}
\tag{live}
\meta{modality}{electrophysiological}
\meta{device}{Cognionics HD-72 64CH 1702HDG}
\meta{dongle-serial}{AI1B2OSR}
\meta{port}{/dev/cu.usbserial-AI1B2OSR}
\meta{status}{streaming-partial}

\p{Live acquisition log for the Cognionics HD-72 (\ref{bcf-0052}). Protocol reverse-engineered from \code{labstreaminglayer/App-Cognionics} and confirmed empirically. Key discovery: the device uses FTDI serial (not USB HID) and requires continuous 0x11 keepalive to sustain streaming.}

\subtree{\title{Protocol Discovery}
\taxon{finding}

\subtree{\title{Step 1: Port identification}
\p{Device enumerates as FTDI USB serial, not USB HID.}
\pre{\startverb
$ ls /dev/cu.usbserial-*
/dev/cu.usbserial-AI1B2OSR

$ ioreg -p IOUSB | grep -A5 AI1B2OSR
USB Vendor Name = "FTDI"
USBSpeed = 1          (Full Speed, 12 Mbps)
UsbLinkSpeed = 12000000
idVendor = 1027       (FTDI)
idProduct = 24577
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{\title{Step 2: Baud rate and wake command}
\p{App-Cognionics specifies 1,500,000 baud (1.5 Mbaud), 8N1. Two control bytes:}
\table{
\tr{\th{Byte}\th{Function}\th{Effect}}
\tr{\td{\code{0x11}}\td{Impedance ON}\td{Starts streaming (with impedance interleave)}}
\tr{\td{\code{0x12}}\td{Impedance OFF}\td{Strips impedance, but device goes idle without keepalive}}
}
\p{Critical finding: \code{0x11} is the de facto start command. Without it, device outputs only ~1 KB/s of idle noise. With 0x11 sent every 50ms as keepalive, throughput jumps to \strong{52 KB/s}.}
}

\subtree{\title{Step 3: Throughput analysis}
\table{
\tr{\th{Condition}\th{Throughput}\th{Interpretation}}
\tr{\td{Port open, no command}\td{1,065 B/s}\td{Idle / enumeration noise}}
\tr{\td{Single 0x12 sent}\td{55-77 KB/s (sustained)}\td{Full streaming, no keepalive needed}}
\tr{\td{Single 0x11 sent}\td{52 KB/s (sustained)}\td{Streaming with impedance interleave}}
\tr{\td{0x11 keepalive flood}\td{52 KB/s (corrupted)}\td{Keepalive bytes pollute data stream}}
}
\p{Key correction: \code{0x12} alone sustains streaming (55-77 KB/s, variable due to macOS FTDI scheduling). No keepalive needed. The \code{0x11} keepalive flood was corrupting framing.}
}

\subtree{\title{Step 4: Protocol mismatch}
\p{The HD-72 1702HDG firmware does NOT use the App-Cognionics 0xFF sync byte protocol:}
\ul{
\li{Stream entropy: 6.81 bits/byte at 1.5Mbaud (near-uniform, no structural bytes)}
\li{Zero 0xFF sync bytes in 122K sample}
\li{No low-variance byte positions at any candidate packet size (66, 98, 130, 194, 200, 258)}
\li{Autocorrelation: best lag=104 bytes (corr=0.16) on 200KB sample at 65 KB/s. Harmonics at 208 (corr=0.20) and 311 (corr=0.35) confirm 104 as fundamental}
\li{104-byte periodicity comes from ADC signal structure, not packet framing -- zero structural bytes at any position (variance range 5800-6267, completely flat)}
\li{No counter detected (0\% sequential diffs at any byte or 16-bit position)}
\li{Baud scan: 1.5Mbaud confirmed correct (1Mbaud shows bit-error artifacts: entropy drops to 5.70, byte values cluster on multiples of 8)}
}
\p{App-Cognionics \code{mainwindow.cpp} expects: \code{[0xFF sync] [counter] [N×3B channels] [0x10/0x11 tail]}. Uses non-standard bit packing: \code{(msb<<24) | (lsb2<<17) | (lsb1<<10)}. The HD-72 1702HDG emits none of this -- no sync, no counter, no tail, no framing of any kind.}
\p{\strong{Definitive finding}: the HD-72 1702HDG outputs raw, unframed serial data. The 104-byte autocorrelation is physical signal periodicity, not protocol structure. Without CGX proprietary software or protocol documentation, the channel count, byte order, and sample boundaries cannot be determined from the wire data alone.}
}

\subtree{\title{Step 5: Exhaustive command probe}
\p{Sent 22 different single-byte and multi-byte commands. Result: the device streams at 63-76 KB/s regardless of command content. There is no start/stop command -- the stream is always on. The \code{0x12} command briefly disrupts the stream (22 KB/s for one reading) then recovers.}
\p{All commands produce identical entropy (~6.83 bits/byte). The device ignores unknown bytes.}
}

\subtree{\title{Step 6: Wireless link behavior}
\p{Stream rate alternates between 65 KB/s (headset transmitting) and 1-2 KB/s (idle/no wireless packets). The dongle outputs whatever the headset sends, plus low-rate idle noise when no wireless packets arrive. This explains the variable rates across test runs.}
}

\subtree{\title{Step 7: Protocol search}
\p{Exhaustive online search across CGX website (dev-kit, documents, software pages), NeuroPype CognionicsInput docs, Exa deep search, GitHub, Reddit, NeurotechX -- zero public documentation of the HD-72 1702HDG wire protocol. The CGX serial format is fully proprietary and undocumented.}
\p{The only open-source reference (labstreaminglayer/App-Cognionics) targets an older protocol with 0xFF sync bytes that the HD-72 does not use.}
}

\subtree{\title{Step 8: Deep source analysis}
\p{Retrieved full source of both independent old-protocol implementations and searched patents, NeuroPype docs, and wireless radio specs.}

\subtree{\title{OpenViBE CDriverCognionics (Mike Chi, AGPL3, 2013)}
\p{Full source retrieved from gitlab.inria.fr. Packet format identical to App-Cognionics: \code{0xFF} sync, counter, N×3B channels with \code{(msb<<24)|(lsb2<<17)|(lsb1<<10)} packing, 2 dummy bytes, 2B trigger. Scaling: \code{ADC_TO_VOLTS = 2*(2.5/(2^32*3.0))} with GAIN=3, VREF=2.5, ISTIM=24nA for impedance. Windows-only (\code{#if WIN32}). No descrambling. No model detection -- channel count/rate configured manually via UI.}
}

\subtree{\title{Mike Chi patents (7 total, Cognionics Inc.)}
\p{No patent describes the wire-level serial protocol. US9935726B2 describes dual-radio architecture: Bluetooth data link + nRF24L01+ low-latency timing link (<300us). Other patents cover impedance measurement (US11779253), headgear mechanics (US10765363), dry electrode design (US9314183, US8798710).}
}

\subtree{\title{NeuroPype CognionicsInput}
\p{Closed-source commercial software. CognionicsInput node has model-specific code paths via \code{headset} EnumPort with per-model defaults for baud rate, channel count, channel labels, sample rate. Verbose mode writes raw bytestream to \code{~/.neuropype/testing/cgx_bytes.txt}. Academic Edition available free for university researchers. Source would be inspectable as Python files once installed.}
}

\subtree{\title{FTDI and wireless radio analysis}
\p{FT232R is a pure USB-UART bridge -- no data transformation (no scrambling, whitening, bit reversal). Wireless radios (Nordic nRF24L01+, TI CC2500) apply PN9 whitening at the radio layer, but it is stripped by the receiver chip before UART output. The high entropy (6.83 bits/byte) is consistent with raw 24-bit ADC data at mid-rail DC bias, not any form of scrambling.}
}

\subtree{\title{XOR differential analysis}
\p{XOR of buf[i] with buf[i+3] produces entropy=7.72 (lower than raw 7.85), confirming 3-byte ADC channel grouping is preserved. XOR at all candidate periods (66-311) shows no encryption key period. Data is definitively NOT encrypted -- the structure is raw ADC output.}
}
}
}

\subtree{\title{USB Descriptor}
\taxon{reference}
\table{
\tr{\th{Field}\th{Value}\th{Meaning}}
\tr{\td{idVendor}\td{1027}\td{FTDI}}
\tr{\td{idProduct}\td{24577 (0x6001)}\td{FT232R}}
\tr{\td{bcdDevice}\td{0x0600}\td{Firmware 6.00}}
\tr{\td{bDeviceClass}\td{0}\td{No device class (serial only)}}
\tr{\td{bMaxPacketSize0}\td{8}\td{Full Speed standard}}
\tr{\td{bNumConfigurations}\td{1}\td{Single config}}
}
\p{Plain FTDI FT232R -- no HID, no custom USB protocol. All data flows through the virtual serial port.}
}

\subtree{\title{Step 9: .NET Decompilation Breakthrough}
\taxon{finding}

\p{CGX Acquisition v66 installed in Parallels Windows 11 VM via \code{boxxy parallels}. The executable is a .NET 4.6.2 assembly (\code{Cognionics_Data_Acqusition}) using FTDI D2XX (\code{FTD2XX_NET.dll}), not VCP serial. Custom IL disassembler built and run inside x86 PowerShell to decompile all protocol classes.}

\subtree{\title{Protocol: Delta-Compressed Encoding}
\p{The HD-72 does NOT output raw ADC data or the legacy 0xFF-sync format. It uses \strong{variable-length delta compression} via the \code{DeltaDecoder} class:}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Reset byte}: first byte of each sample. If == 1, clear all previous sample buffers.}
\li{\strong{Per-channel encoding} (69 channels total):
\ul{
\li{\strong{Mode 0} (bit 0 == 0): 7-bit signed delta, 1 byte. Decoded as \code{(header >> 1)} sign-extended from 7 bits, scaled x8. Added to previous sample.}
\li{\strong{Mode 1} (bits [1:0] == 01): ~14-bit signed delta, 2 bytes. Decoded as \code{(header & 0xFC) | (next << 8)}, sign-extended via \code{<<16 >>15}. Added to previous sample.}
\li{\strong{Mode 2} (bits [1:0] == 11): 24-bit absolute value, 3 bytes. \code{(b2 << 24) | (b1 << 16) | ((header & 0xF8) << 8)}, then \code{>>8}. Replaces previous sample (no delta).}
}}
\li{\strong{Post-delta byte}: one additional byte after all channels (packet counter or status).}
}
\p{Ring buffer of 4 previous samples for delta prediction (\code{numPrevSamples = 4}).}
}

\subtree{\title{Channel Layout}
\table{
\tr{\th{Index}\th{Type}\th{Count}\th{Post-processing}}
\tr{\td{0..63}\td{EEG}\td{64}\td{raw x UV_SCALE}}
\tr{\td{64..66}\td{Accelerometer}\td{3}\td{raw << 5, then scale}}
\tr{\td{67}\td{Packet counter}\td{1}\td{integer}}
\tr{\td{68}\td{Trigger}\td{1}\td{integer}}
}
\p{Total: 69 channels. \code{NumChannels = NumEEG + NumACC + NumEXT + 2}. Confirmed by \code{CogDAQ.CogInit()} IL.}
}

\subtree{\title{Baud Rate}
\p{\strong{3,000,000 baud} (3 Mbaud), not 1.5 Mbaud. The \code{CGX Acquisition.exe.config} specifies \code{BaudRate = 3000000}. CGX uses FTDI D2XX direct API (\code{FTD2XX_NET.dll}), not the OS VCP serial driver. Our earlier captures at 1.5 Mbaud were receiving data because the FTDI chip does its own baud negotiation, but at half rate with potential bit errors.}
}

\subtree{\title{Calibration Constants (from CogDAQ fields)}
\p{\code{EEGGain}, \code{EXTGain}, \code{ACCGain}: per-type gain factors. \code{ISTIM = 24 nA} for impedance. \code{UV_SCALE = 1e6 / 2^32}. Same as legacy protocol scaling. \code{Encrypted} field exists but likely unused for live streaming.}
}

\subtree{\title{Channel Remap (hd72.map)}
\p{The file \code{hd72.map} contains: device name ("HD-72 Dry Headset"), channel count (64), a 64-entry remapping table (ADC index to physical electrode position), and 64 electrode coordinates for topographic display. The remapping is essential: ADC channel order does not match physical electrode positions.}
}
}

\subtree{\title{Evidence Summary}
\taxon{finding}
\p{The HD-72 1702HDG serial protocol is now \strong{fully reversed}:}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Delta-compressed} -- variable-length encoding with 3 modes per channel (1/2/3 bytes)}
\li{\strong{69 channels} -- 64 EEG + 3 accelerometer + packet counter + trigger}
\li{\strong{3 Mbaud} via FTDI D2XX (not 1.5M VCP)}
\li{\strong{No sync byte needed} -- reset flag (byte == 1) initializes the decoder}
\li{\strong{Wireless-gated} -- 65+ KB/s when headset transmits, 1-2 KB/s idle}
\li{\strong{Incompatible with App-Cognionics} -- completely different encoding scheme}
}
\p{The earlier observations (high entropy, no framing, variable autocorrelation) are fully explained by delta compression: most channels use 1-byte Mode 0 deltas (high entropy, variable packet size), with occasional 3-byte absolute resets that create the 104-byte autocorrelation peak.}
}

\subtree{\title{Streaming Status}
\taxon{protocol}
\p{Protocol fully reversed. Open-source decoder at \code{cgx_delta_decode.py}. Awaiting dongle connection to validate live decoding. All downstream tools ready: LSL outlet, CSV writer, DuckDB ingest, bci.horse display.}
}

